\subsection{ Inverting op-amp circuit}
 
\medskip \centerline{\includegraphics{01029.eps}} 
 

To simulate an ideal operational amplifier in SPICE, we use a voltage-dependent voltage source as a differential amplifier with extremely high gain.  The "\texttt{e}" card sets up the dependent voltage source with four nodes, 3 and 0 for voltage output, and 1 and 0 for voltage input.  No power supply is needed for the dependent voltage source, unlike a real operational amplifier.  The voltage gain is set at 999,000 in this case.  The input voltage source (V$_{1}$) sweeps from 0 to 3.5 volts in 0.05 volt steps.
 

\bigskip 
 

\textbf{Netlist:}
 

\begingroup \vskip\parskip \everypar={\nobreak} \obeyspaces \frenchspacing \tt \obeylines \parskip=0pt \parindent=0pt 
Inverting opamp
v1 2 0 dc 
e 3 0 0 1 999k
r1 3 1 3.29k
r2 1 2 1.18k
.dc v1 0 3.5 0.05
.print dc v(3,0)
.end
\endgroup 
